{"questionId":"22017","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>It is known that the weights of male Persian cats are normally distributed with mean <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>kg</mtext></math>&nbsp;and variance <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><msup><mn>5</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo> </mo><msup><mtext>kg</mtext><mn>2</mn></msup></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A group of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>80</mn></math> male Persian cats are drawn from this population.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The male cats are now joined by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>80</mn></math> female Persian cats. The female cats are drawn&nbsp;from a population whose weights are normally distributed with mean <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>kg</mtext></math> and standard&nbsp;deviation <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>45</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>kg</mtext></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Ten female cats are chosen at random.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>N</mi></math> be the number of cats weighing over <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>62</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>kg</mtext></math>.</p>\n<p>Find the variance of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>N</mi></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mi>p</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>p</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>39</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>38946</mn><mo>…</mo></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong><em>A1</em></strong></p>\n<p><br><em><strong>[1 mark]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22017","referenceCode":"21M.2.AHL.TZ2.2d.ii","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Let N be the number of cats weighing over 4.62 kg. Find the variance of N.","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"d.ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.8—Binomial distribution"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}